Michael, review
Markus Schleinzer's debut film about the routine of a paedophile, Michael, makes for heart-stopping, mind-frazzling cinema. 4
Michael Fuith as Michael By Robbie Collin
5:24PM GMT 01 Mar 2012
Follow Comments
18 cert, 96 min
Dir: Markus Schleinzer. Starring Michael Fuith, David Rauchenberger When the door to Michael’s basement first swings open, the inky blackness beyond it is as unfathomable as it is impenetrable. Michael (Michael Fuith) is a paedophile. He is 35 years old, with a moderately successful career in insurance and a ten-year-old boy imprisoned in his cellar. In his directorial debut, the Austrian filmmaker Markus Schleinzer shows us Michael and his prisoner Wolfgang (David Rauchenberger) going about their daily routine: food is fried and eaten, plates are washed, television is watched until bedtime. What we don’t see – or rather what Schleinzer doesn’t show us – are almost any explicit details of abuse or rape. But our minds’ eyes fill in the blanks, and by the sheer power of association, the routine itself becomes terrifying. Schleinzer could hardly have chosen a more difficult subject, but he treats it with an unnerving simplicity, shorn of sensationalism or obvious moral cues. Comparisons with the work of Michael Haneke are inevitable but deserved, and the similarities are surely no accident: Schleinzer has often worked as Haneke’s casting director.
Related Articles
This Means War, review
02 Mar 2012
Project X, review
01 Mar 2012
Individual scenes stick in the mind like stains: Michael talking to a second young boy at a go-karting centre, Michael happily singing a Boney M song in the car after being promoted, Michael bringing buckets of snow down to the cellar so he can throw snowballs at Wolfgang. The ending delivers the gut-wrenching catharsis we crave, but with an acid afterburn. This is heart-stopping, mind-frazzling cinema; hard to recommend but even harder not to. Film Reviews
