Deep in the forest, I wait expectantly for my prey – the secretive wild boar
Left to themselves, the population of wild boar - now well established in Sussex, Dorset and Gloucestershire - would treble annually. Tusk, tusk: Simon Barr and Clive Aslet look in vain for a boar from their eyrie in a Sussex wood Photo: Andrew Hasson	By Clive Aslet
7:30AM GMT 27 Dec 2011
Comments
Ssssh! We are sitting in a wooden cabin on stilts, somewhere in Sussex. Nothing stirs. The last time the animal we are looking for was spotted in significant numbers was in in the Middle Ages, rootling through the deep-pile oak leaf carpet of the forest floor, just before it was hunted to extinction. But three populations of wild boar have now become established in Britain, following their escape from farms which breed them for their excellent meat. While the ferocious creatures of lore have a tendency to burst from the undergrowth, the sounders – or boar families – of Sussex and Dorset live mostly peaceful, retired lives, keeping out of sight of poachers. However, this month visitors to the Forest of Dean have been enjoying close encounters with the boar. They pet them, give them food, and presumably imagine that the creatures have the happy-go-lucky attitude of Pumbaa, the warthog in The Lion King. But as Simon Barr, owner of the hide, observes, “like any wild animal, they can be unpredictable”. Get between a sow and its young, and you won’t find it singing Hakuna Matata.
In this health-and-safety-conscious age, no landowner wants to risk a lawsuit, should a visitor find him or herself on the business end of a well-honed tusk. An adult boar, weighing 200kg, can be the size of a family sofa. When they charge, you know about it.
Sows produce eight or nine piglets per litter, and are capable of breeding twice a year. Left to themselves, numbers of wild boar would treble annually. This year has been a successful breeding season due to abundant acorns, beechmast and sweet chestnut. Consequently, the Forestry Commission, owners of the Forest of Dean, have decided that a family of boar popular with visitors known as the Beechenhurst Six will have to take its chances in a cull with 1,000 others. Related Articles
Sorry, Santa, they’re only here for the deer
23 Dec 2011
Rural species adopt new urban lifestyles
20 Dec 2011
Unemployment among young in rural areas rising faster than other areas
18 Dec 2011
'A wound in the loveliest of places’
17 Dec 2011
The colourful life of my father, James Herriot
16 Dec 2011
For Simon, the problem is more about conserving a healthy population. His patch is an 800-acre block of woodland, to which he buys the shooting rights. On it, he sustainably manages 300 or so wild boar by carefully selecting targets. They are likely to be young males: “Wild boars live in matriarchal groups, headed by a lead sow. She shows the group where to live and feed. Take out the sow and there will be a mass dispersal, causing damage to the farmland outside the wood.”
Unlike grey squirrels, which ring-bark growing trees, wild boars are the forester’s friend. Blessed with bony snouts, they root through the ground looking for invertebrates and bluebell bulbs, rotavating the earth and facilitating natural regeneration. Many farmers, however, argue that the wild boar is a pest.
Wild boar may or may not be regarded as native to the countryside – they were reintroduced when several escaped from farms during the Great Storm of 1987. But, like other wildlife, they should be properly managed and humanely treated. As Zac Goldsmith MP suggested last month, this ought to mean a closed season; if a sow is shot during spring or summer, her piglets will be left to starve. In Eastern Europe, wild boar is a prime quarry species, and enthusiasts pay big money for the sport of shooting it. As with venison, they have a system by which the meat is tagged as soon as it is shot, so it can be traced through the supply chain, thereby reducing poaching.
For us right now, the problem is not so much avoiding an onslaught of wild boar as seeing one specimen. These beasts operate to a Proustian schedule. They get up when the rest of the world is going to bed. There is a reason that Simon has installed comfortable office chairs in his hide, despite their less than rustic appearance; he is often here all night.
From our eyrie above the Sussex wood, we see a glorious cock pheasant. On terra firma, Simon finds a wallow; a large, pig-shaped mud bath in a stream. We stomp around a grove of trees, observing one last fallen apple, which will probably be gone by morning.
But I do eventually find a boar. This happens in Simon’s partly 16th-century cottage, shared with Selena, whom he married last month (Guess what was served at the wedding feast…). To judge from its expression, it’s just as well the taxidermist got to it first.
Clive Aslet is editor at large of Country Life
