The financial benefits of living with your partner
Even if you just live together, it's worth buying as a couple whenever you can.
Image 1 of 2	Darren and Emma Whitlock have saved money by pooling their finances. Image 1 of 2	Some of the biggest savings for couples include joint home insurance policies. Photo: Alamy	By Rosie Murray-West
7:00AM GMT 17 Mar 2013
Follow Comments
Darren Whitlock, 31, and his wife, Emma, have saved money by pooling their finances. They have taken out a joint account with Santander, which gives them cashback on all of the bills they pay. They also share a mobile phone contract and car insurance policies. Mr Whitlock, from Potter’s Bar in Hertfordshire, said that previously Emma paid the bills and he paid the mortgage, but the cashback from the joint account was adding up to £200 or £300 a year. “We already have a mortgage together so our finances are joined as it is,” he said. Living together can have financial, as well as emotional, benefits, new figures have shown. However, joint finances can be a double-edged sword. Exclusive research from Aviva shows that over half of households are missing out on the savings they could gain from opening joint accounts, having joint insurance policies and using products such as family railcards. The research shows that the average household could save over £350 a year by amalgamating some financial products, but that many people are not taking advantage of this. Cohabiting couples, the fastest-growing family type in Britain, are the least likely to merge their finances. Related Articles
'I was charged twice for airline tickets'
20 Mar 2013
'My travel card didn't work abroad'
20 Mar 2013
Home owners fear rising costs
15 Mar 2013
'What shall I do with my inheritance?'
15 Mar 2013
'I paid £9 for yogurt worth £133'
14 Mar 2013
Spain faces EU legal action over 'illegal' hosptial bills for tourists
30 May 2013
Some of the biggest savings for couples include joint home insurance policies. The typical saving that can be made by a couple on these products is £84 – 10pc of the average spend. Buying a family railcard can also save an average of £99 a year. “At a time when many families are feeling the squeeze, reviewing finances and consolidating spending to make the most of multi-person discounts could be a simple and effective way to save money,” said Heather Smith, director of marketing at Aviva. “In most cases changing your policies or applying for joint contracts is much easier than you think and savings can be substantial.”
However, multi-car insurance is not always cheapest, so ensure that you shop around with both single and multi car policies, rather than assuming the discount will be the best bet. Other places where couples can potentially save include mobile phone contracts and breakdown cover. Families who use a joint paid-for bank account can often get cover for everyone’s mobile phones, for example, as well as family travel insurance more cheaply than joint policies. However, it is important to check that the cover you are getting matches your needs, and that you are not excluded from claiming due to your age, or any medical conditions you might have. Before you share your finances, it is important to understand the risks that merging your money can bring. One of the most important assets you have is your credit record, which will be checked every time you apply for a mortgage, a loan, or even a mobile phone contract. The credit record shows all the financial products that you own as well as your track record on paying them off. Based on this record, financial companies will decide whether to give you a loan or mortgage, and also whether to give you a good rate or not. Once you merge your finances, however, creditors can see that you have a financial relationship with another person. In the eyes of the banks and building societies, your creditworthiness is then affected by the other person’s financial decision. So if your partner is late paying off his credit card, you can suffer too. Your credit report, which you can see for £2 if you apply by post to Experian, Equifax or Call Credit (three major credit rating agencies), or for free with noddle.co.uk in return for viewing some advertisements, will show any financial connections you are deemed to have with other people. There is an Association box in your credit report where you can view this, but you will not be able to view their credit information to see whether it is good or bad. If you split up with your partner, or fear that their credit record is spoiling yours, you can apply for a financial disassociation. You will need to do this with all three agencies. Experian’s is available at tinyurl.com/cqt3f99, while Callcredit’s form needs to be posted but is online at tinyurl.com/d5ydhqs. Equifax requires you to have a credit report number in order to access these details at equifax.co.uk. You should also be aware when taking out what looks like a “joint” credit card that there is no such thing. Often, a credit card company will offer you a second card for a partner when you take out the first. This can be useful if you are racking up Air Miles or cashback on your spending. However, you need to be aware that the person who applied for the cards is solely responsible for the debt on both of them. If you do split up, untangle your finances as quickly as possible. Close any joint accounts, and credit cards with second cardholders on them. If you are renting, notify the landlord and make sure the name of the person who is moving out is removed from the tenancy agreement. Finally, if you have a new partner and believe that they have had debt problems in the past, make sure you keep your finances completely separate. That means no joint names on bills, loans or credit cards. It takes up to six years for their financial issues to be removed from their credit record, so make sure that yours isn’t affected. • Want to know more? Watch out for the updates in our weekly newsletter: Sign up for free
