The last survivor of the Lisbon Maru
Seventy years ago, a cargo ship sank with thousands of Allied PoWs trapped in the hold by the Japanese
'What can I remember? Well, if you had been to hell, you’d know what it was like. It was hell,' says Dennis Morley, 92 Photo: JAY WILLIAMS	By Malcolm Moore
7:00AM BST 30 Sep 2012
Follow Comments
The first torpedo came at 7 in the morning, when the Lisbon Maru, with her cargo of nearly 2,000 British and Canadian prisoners, was off the Chinese coast near Shanghai.
The rusting Japanese freighter was taking the men, captured after the surrender of Hong Kong at the end of 1941, to slave in Japan’s dockyards and ports, its coal mines and factories. But it never reached its destination.
With no flags or markings to warn that it was carrying prisoners below decks, and with nearly 800 Japanese soldiers visible on board, it appeared a perfect target to an American submarine.
Tomorrow marks the 70th anniversary of what turned out to be one of the most callous incidents in a particularly callous arena of the Second World War. As the crippled vessel slowly began to sink, a Japanese decision to batten down the hatches on the prisoners below, then to shoot mercilessly at those who managed to escape and swim for it, led to the deaths of nearly 1,000 men.
“What can I remember? Well, if you had been to hell, you’d know what it was like. It was hell,” said Dennis Morley, 92, who was a private in the Royal Scots at the time.
