Mr Morley may well be the last survivor of the tragedy. Tony Banham, a Hong Kong-based historian who has written an account of the sinking, said: “One by one, the others I was in touch with have all gone quiet. [But] there could still be others. I am in touch with other prisoners of war who are older [than Dennis].”
The anniversary will go unmarked in China, Japan and in the UK, and it comes as tensions in the sea that separates Asia’s two great powers are rising once again – not least because of the bitter memories of other wartime atrocities inflicted on China and its people by Japan’s army. The sailing of the Lisbon Maru was ill-fated from the start. After nearly a year in PoW camps in Hong Kong, three quarters of the men on board were sick when they boarded, with dysentery, diphtheria or beriberi.
The ship’s three vast and gloomy cargo holds were filled with two-tier wooden platforms covered in thin rush matting. Each man was allotted 18 inches of space.
The bulk of the prisoners were from three regiments, the Royal Scots, Middlesex Regiment and Royal Artillery.
“My lot was right on the bottom of the number two hold,” said Mr Morley. “And being on the bottom, we were inundated by faeces falling from the people above.”
The Lisbon Maru was a hulking freight ship that displaced some 7,000 tons. She was 22 years old by the time she set sail from Hong Kong, and had recently been used both to transport metal and then troops.
When she was spotted by the USS Grouper six miles off the Zhoushan archipelago, the American submarine commander could have had no inkling of her cargo.
Mr Banham’s recorded what happened after the Grouper opened fire in his book, The Sinking of the Lisbon Maru.
“On the morning of October 1st, about 7am, most people were awake and awaiting the first meal of the day. Suddenly a loud noise, like air escaping from a tyre, was heard and one could not tell whether it was inboard or outboard. We later realised it was a torpedo that had missed,” said Alf Hunt, who was also a prisoner.
It was the fourth torpedo, a one-and-a-half ton, 20ft missile, that hit the stern. Immediately, the Japanese ordered all prisoners down into the holds as the ship slowly began to sink.
“We firmly believed the Japs would not let us drown. They could not be so heartless that they would let 1,800 helpless men die,” said James Miller of the Royal Scots.
But in fact the Japanese command battened down the hatches on the three holds and then stretched tarpaulin and set up a machine-gun post to shoot any escapees.
As the ship went down, 10 Japanese vessels in the area came to its aid, ferrying off the 778 Japanese soldiers. But the British prisoners were left behind, frantically trying to pump water out of their holds.
“After a while there was a moment when the panic sunk in,” remembered Mr Morley. “But that did not last long. Eventually some bright fellow who had a knife managed to cut the canvas and get the hatch open. The first lot that got out were shot by the Japs on the bridge, but eventually they managed to get over and kill them.
“Then there was a panic on the ladder, but one officer, I think his name was Cuthbertson, took control and got everyone to go up the ladder one by one and eventually we all got up. Once we were clear, Cuthbertson went back down to check there was no one left behind.”
In all, 1,750 prisoners made it off the ship and into the water. Many of them started swimming for the Japanese rescue flotilla, but were greeted with more rifle fire.
Not only did Japanese soldiers strafe the water, but some men who climbed up on to Japanese boats were shot in the head and dumped back into the sea.
Mr Morley, however, was eventually picked up by a Japanese craft, given some “green tea and a cigarette”, and taken to Shanghai.
For around 300 of his fellow prisoners, rescue came in the form of Chinese fishermen, who risked Japanese fire to sail out from the nearby islands and pick them up.
“My father was 13 at the time and he helped to rescue the people coming onshore,” said Liang Yingji, 45. “Most of the people who were involved have passed away now, although my father is still alive. The fishermen saved 338 of the prisoners in total. They risked their lives to do it.”
Afterwards, however, the fishermen did not report the rescue to the government, shying away from any praise. One of the British prisoners gave his mouth organ to a fisherman in gratitude, but the islanders were so poor that it was traded for a bag of rice.
A museum on Dongji island, where the fishermen took the prisoners and cared for them in the local temple, was opened in 2009, with a replica of the ship and clippings from the reports in the British press. Beer barrels that floated up from the wreck, which lies in around 100ft of water, are on display, as are the mess tins and cutlery that some of the prisoners had with them.
No one has yet made a proper dive to examine the wreck, however. Steve Chan, who runs a dive shop in Wanchai, Hong Kong, said he had “touched” the boat, but been unable to see it properly because of poor visibility.
The survivors spent only a day on the island before a Japanese ship landed and recaptured them. They were taken to Shanghai, where a roll call showed that 846 men had perished.
Three soldiers managed to hide in a cave on the island, and then made their way to Chongqing, then the capital of non-occupied China.
From there they were eventually shipped to Japan, where another 246 died before the winter was out. Mr Morley spent the remainder of the war in forced labour, first in the maritime city of Kobe and then at a small port called Fusiki – a tough existence, but one in which it was necessary for him and fellow prisoners at least to be fed, in order that they could work productively.
For that, he is thankful: when the war ended and Americans finally arrived, he and fellow forced labourers glimpsed how their lives in Japan might have been even worse as they were driven to the ships waiting to carry them homeward.
“We saw the PoW camps where they were all skeletons,” he said.
He recalls with pleasure their gradual progress towards Britain. “They shipped us first to the Philippines and then to Canada,” he said. “We went on board the USS Admiral Hughes to Vancouver. We crossed Canada and at every place we stopped we got a hero’s welcome, including a Native Indian war dance in the Rockies.”
In September 1946, the Japanese interpreter on board the Lisbon Maru, Niimori Genichiro, was sentenced to 15 years in prison. The captain, Kyoda Shigeru, who had at first resisted orders to batten down the hatches, was tried before a different tribunal that year and given seven years in prison.
Lieutenant Wada Hideo, who outranked Kyoda as a military officer, and who overruled him and ordered the hatches shut, died before he could face justice.
When Dennis Morley returned to the UK, he was transferred by the Army to work in its medical corps. He then moved to a civilian hospital as an orderly.
He had two wives, his first died very young, at 30, but bore him a daughter. When he married his second wife, he inherited two boys and a girl. Mr Morley now lives in Stroud, Gloucestershire. He has made a few trips back to Hong Kong – and went on a “peace and reconciliation” trip to Japan in 2007.
“I’m glad I did that because I have wiped everything off now and I am at peace,” he said. “I do not have any bad dreams. I am a happy man.”
